        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "Y",
        "tooltip": "This grid depicts the interpreted vertical thickness (isochore) in metres between the N60 and Seabed seismic horizons mapped within the Southeast Province of the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity (namely the Canterbury-Great South Basin). This isochore interval encompasses rocks of c. 05-0 Ma age (Early Pliocene to Holocene). For more information about the seismic horizon naming scheme used in this project please refer to: Strogen, D.P.; King, P.R. 2014. A new Zealandia-wide seismic horizon naming scheme. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The TWT and depth grids, from which this grid was derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015.5 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT or depth maps in this project. The TWT and depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 5.8), edited as needed to account for gridding errors, and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire SEP area the "smoothness" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Canterbury Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas of the SEP such as the Pukaki Basin to the south east and the Rakiura Trough to the south east, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 50 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. For further information on these data, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Southeast Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23c.",

        "tooltip": "Grid depicting the modelled depth, in milliseconds, beneath sea level to the K80 horizon in the Southeast Province mapping area (Canterbury-Great South Basin), for the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity. The grid was generated in Paradigm 2015.5 SeisEarth software using a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT or depth maps in this project. The TWT and depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 5.8), edited as needed to account for gridding errors, and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire SEP area the "smoothness" of the TWT maps varies accordingly. In the central Canterbury Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas such as the southern part of the SEP and the Rakiura Trough to the southwest, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 50 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines.For more information about the depth conversion and gridding process used, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al.         "showOpacitySlider": "Y",
        "tooltip": "Grid depicting the Transformation Ratio (oil generation) for marine rocks of Eocene age (approximates Waipawa ("Tartan") Formation). The grid indicates predicted transformation of organic matter at the base of the unit regardless of source rock presence and richness. Multi-1D modelling was used to reconstruct the basin thermal history and to predict maturity at present day. Transformation ratio maps were produced using the BM1D basin modelling code developed by GNS Science which is based on the 1D finite-element conductive heat flow package Bassim. The Multi-1D basin simulation code is applied to 1 km x 1 km cells across the SEP basin grids. Stratigraphic thickness, age, temperature and paleobathymetric data are combined with mathematical relationships describing sediment properties during progressive compaction to derive burial and thermal maturity histories for each cell. Heat flow is applied at the base of the model, using an approach consistent with that described in Armstrong et al. (1996) to fit thermal calibration data. Stratigraphic thickness, lithological data and paleobathymetry data are based on seismic interpretation and paleogeographic maps developed under the APP program over the SEP. For further information on these data, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017.         "baseLayer": "N",

        "toolTipField": "Raster",
        "showInLegend": "Y",
        "showLegendGraphic": "Y",
        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "Y",
        "tooltip": "Grid depicting the Transformation Ratio (gas generation) for coaly source rocks of mid-Cretaceous age, deposited during an early syn-rift phase (Includes Hoiho Group). The grid indicates predicted transformation of organic matter at the base of the unit regardless of source rock presence and richness. Multi-1D modelling was used to reconstruct the basin thermal history and to predict maturity at present day. Transformation ratio maps were produced using the BM1D basin modelling code developed by GNS Science which is based on the 1D finite-element conductive heat flow package Bassim. The Multi-1D basin simulation code is applied to 1 km x 1 km cells across the SEP basin grids. Stratigraphic thickness, age, temperature and paleobathymetric data are combined with mathematical relationships describing sediment properties during progressive compaction to derive burial and thermal maturity histories for each cell. Heat flow is applied at the base of the model, using an approach consistent with that described in Armstrong et al. (1996) to fit thermal calibration data. Stratigraphic thickness, lithological data and paleobathymetry data are based on seismic interpretation and paleogeographic maps developed under the APP program over the SEP. For further information on these data, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Southeast Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23c.",

        "showLegendGraphic": "N",
        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "Y",
        "tooltip": "Grid depicting the modelled depth, in metres, beneath sea level to the Seabed horizon in the Southeast Province mapping area (Canterbury-Great South Basin), for the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity. The grid was generated in Paradigm 2015.5 SeisEarth software using a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT or depth maps in this project. The TWT and depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 5.8), edited as needed to account for gridding errors, and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire SEP area the \"smoothness\" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Canterbury Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas such as the southern part of the SEP and the Rakiura Trough to the southwest, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 50 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines.For more information about the depth conversion and gridding process used, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Southeast Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23c.",

    {
        "layerid": 1195,
        "library": "APP_NWP_Library",
        "libGroup": "ISOCHORE (THICKNESS) GRIDS (metres)/TOTAL SEDIMENT THICKNESS (mid-Cretaceous to Recent)",
        "layerName": "gns:NWP_Isochore_contours_Total_Sediment___mid_Cret__to_Recent_",
        "name": "NWP_Isochore contours Total Sediment  (mid-Cret  to Recent)",
        "baseLayer": "N",
        "serverUrl": "https://data.gns.cri.nz/webmaps/petroleum/wms",
        "visible": "Y",
        "allowExternalDownload": "Y",
        "toolTipField": "Contour",
        "showInLegend": "Y",
        "showLegendGraphic": "Y",
        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "N",
        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains contours that depict the interpreted vertical thickness (isochore) in metres for between the Basement and Seabed seismic horizons mapped within the Northwest Province of the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity (namely the Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). This isochore interval encompasses rocks of c. 110-0 Ma age. For more information about the seismic horizon naming scheme used in this project please refer to: Strogen, D.P.; King, P.R. 2014. A new Zealandia-wide seismic horizon naming scheme. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The depth and isochore grids, from which these contours were derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT or depth maps in this project. The TWT and depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 4.61), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids, imported and contoured with Esri's ArcGIS software. Contour intervals are 500 m. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire NWP area the \"smoothness\" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Taranaki Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas of the NWP such as the Deepwater Taranaki Basin to the west and Reinga Basin in the north, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 30 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. For further information on these data, please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest P",

    {

        "name": "4DT southern Taranaki Basin mapping area",
        "baseLayer": "N",
        "serverUrl": "https://data.gns.cri.nz/webmaps/petroleum/wms",
        "visible": "Y",

        "toolTipField": "ID",

        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "N",
        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains, as a polygon feature, the outline of the southern Taranaki Basin mapping area, part of GNS Science's \"4D Taranaki Project\" (4DT) within the Petroleum Basins Research (PBR) programme. It is recognised that whilst the APP NWP seismic mapping has been undertaken at an appropriate resolution for a frontier basin, GNS Science has over the past decade put significant effort into mapping, modelling, and depth conversion in the southern Taranaki Basin region (refer Bull et al., 2015: Depth structure maps, isopach maps and a regional velocity model from the southern Taranaki Basin (4D Taranaki Project). GNS Science Data Series 12c). In particular, the more sophisticated velocity modelling in the southern Taranaki Basin results in a more robust depth conversion in the areas that have experienced significant uplift and erosion during the Miocene compressional phases. Due to the availability of better resolution depth-converted data in the south, the APP's NWP grids were overwritten with the relevant southern Taranaki Basin mapped intervals to take advantage of this more robust depth conversion. As the cell size of the Bull et al. (2015) grids is finer than the NWP grids, the former were down sampled to 1 km x 1 km cell size to match the NWP gridding. Although the TWT interpretation is constant across the models' boundary, it was found that due to the different depth conversion methods applied there was a marked step in between depth grids. It was decided to leave this footprint artefact to help differentiate between the two modelled areas rather than smoothing the join.",

Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The TWT and depth grids, from which this grid was derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015.5 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT or depth maps in this project. The TWT and depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 5.8), edited as needed to account for gridding errors, and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. In the central Canterbury Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas such as the southern part of the SEP and the Rakiura Trough to the southwest, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 50 km. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The TWT and depth grids, from which this grid was derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015.5 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT or depth maps in this project. The TWT and depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 5.8), edited as needed to account for gridding errors, and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire SEP area the \"smoothness\" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Canterbury Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas such as the southern part of the SEP and the Rakiura Trough to the southwest, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 50 km. For further information on these data, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017.         "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains contours that depict the interpreted depth below sea level in milliseconds two-way-time (TWT) to the P00 (c. 66 Ma; base-Paleocene; base of New Zealand Teurian Stage) horizon in the Southeast Province of the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity (namely the Canterbury-Great South Basin). For more information about the seismic horizon naming scheme used in this project please refer to: Strogen, D.P.; King, P.R. 2014. A new Zealandia-wide seismic horizon naming scheme. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The TWT grids, from which these contours were derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015.5 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT maps in this project. The TWT grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 5.1), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids, imported and contoured with Esri's ArcGIS software. Contour spacing is 250 ms. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire SEP area the \"smoothness\" of the TWT maps varies accordingly. In the central Canterbury Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas such as the southern part of the SEP and the Rakiura Trough to the southwest, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 50 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. For more information about the depth conversion and gridding process used, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017.         "layerName": "gns:SEP_Transformation_ratio_oil__K80__terrestrial__Late_Cret_",
        "name": "Transformation ratio oil (K80, terrestrial, Late Cret)",
        "baseLayer": "N",

        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "N",
        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains contour line features depicting the Transformation Ratio (oil generation) for coaly source rocks of Late Cretaceous age (K80, c. 85 Ma) (Includes Broken River Formation, Hoiho Group, and Horse Range Formation). The contours, in 0.1 increments, indicate predicted transformation of organic matter, through to the present day, at the base of the unit regardless of source rock presence and richness. These contour data and their associated grid should be used in association with the provided \"source rock absence\" maps within the \"APP_SEP_petroleum_generation_grids_A2.mxd\" project. Multi-1D modelling was used to reconstruct the basin thermal history and to predict maturity at present day. Transformation ratio maps were produced using the BM1D basin modelling code developed by GNS Science which is based on the 1D finite-element conductive heat flow package Bassim. The Multi-1D basin simulation code is applied to 1 km x 1 km cells across the SEP basin grids. Stratigraphic thickness, age, temperature and paleobathymetric data are combined with mathematical relationships describing sediment properties during progressive compaction to derive burial and thermal maturity histories for each cell. See Section 6 of the report listed below for description of model calibration. Stratigraphic thickness, lithological data and paleobathymetry data are based on seismic interpretation and paleogeographic maps developed under the APP program over the SEP. For further information on these data, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Southeast Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23c.",

        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains contour line features depicting the Transformation Ratio (oil generation) for coaly source rocks of latest Cretaceous age (K90, c. 77 Ma) (Includes Broken River Formation and Pukeiwitahi Formation). The contours, in 0.1 increments, indicate predicted transformation of organic matter, through to the present day, at the base of the unit regardless of source rock presence and richness. These contour data and their associated grid should be used in association with the provided \"source rock absence\" maps within the \"APP_SEP_petroleum_generation_grids_A2.mxd\" project. Multi-1D modelling was used to reconstruct the basin thermal history and to predict maturity at present day. Transformation ratio maps were produced using the BM1D basin modelling code developed by GNS Science which is based on the 1D finite-element conductive heat flow package Bassim. The Multi-1D basin simulation code is applied to 1 km x 1 km cells across the SEP basin grids. Stratigraphic thickness, age, temperature and paleobathymetric data are combined with mathematical relationships describing sediment properties during progressive compaction to derive burial and thermal maturity histories for each cell. See Section 6 of the report listed below for description of model calibration. Stratigraphic thickness, lithological data and paleobathymetry data are based on seismic interpretation and paleogeographic maps developed under the APP program over the SEP. For further information on these data, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Southeast Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23c.",

It is important to note that a rating of low exploration potential does not conclusively rule it out; rather, there is a high degree of uncertainty associated with presence of one or more of the petroleum system elements.         "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains polygon features that summarise the exploration potential of the Paleocene succession within sedimentary basins in the Northwest Province (Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). Areas where all of the requirements for oil or gas accumulation are present are indicated as having high exploration potential. Areas where all the requirements are not optimum, but may be present are indicated as areas of moderate exploration potential. Areas of low exploration potential indicates that on the basis of currently available open-file information there is a high risk for one or more of the petroleum systems elements not being able to effectively contribute to the petroleum system in that area. It is important to note that a rating of low exploration potential does not conclusively rule it out; rather, there is a high degree of uncertainty associated with presence of one or more of the petroleum system elements. For any given prospective area, more detailed work and data acquisition would be required. For more information about these data please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016.     {
        "layerid": 1806,
        "library": "NZLibrary",
        "libGroup": "Petroleum Systems/Slicks/Temporal Repeats",

        "name": "Nearest Repeat Link",
        "baseLayer": "N",
        "serverUrl": "https://data.gns.cri.nz/webmaps/petroleum/wms",
        "visible": "Y",
        "allowExternalDownload": "N",
        "toolTipField": "category1",
        "showInLegend": "Y",
        "showLegendGraphic": "Y",
        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "N",
        "tooltip": "Repeat_Link.shp (Nearest Repeat Link) Object\r\n\r\nMinimum water depth of 250m has been used due to inaccuracies in the global bathymetric reference data. All distances are taken from the interpreted slick emission points.  \r\n\r\nThe twice water depth value is used as experiments undertaken in the Gulf of Mexico have not shown the deviation from sea floor vent to sea surface have exceeded this. The 4x water depth is to capture slicks where sub surface currents are particularly strong. The ALL5 category is to capture all potential seeps within 5km.\r\n\r\nS2x Seepage-Seepage <= 2x water depth (to max 5km)\r\nS4x Seepage-Seepage <= 4x water depth (to max 5km)\r\nSPU2x Seepage - Pr Un or Pr Un - Pr Un <= 2x water depth (to max 5km)\r\nSPU4x Seepage - Pr Un or Pr Un - Pr Un <= 4x water depth (to max 5km)\r\nSU2x Seepage - Un or Un  Un <= 2x water depth (to max 5km)\r\nSU4x Seepage - Un or Un  Un <= 4x water depth (to max 5km)\r\nALL5  All potential Seepage Slicks <= 5km \r\n\r\nPr Un = Priority Unassigned Slick \r\nUn = Unassigned Slick\r\n\r\nThe Quality field refers to the following weightings dependent on interpreted class:\r\n\r\nSlick Ranking:\r\n\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Seepage Rank 1 = 28 points\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Seepage Rank 2 = 27 points\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Seepage Rank 3 = 26 points\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Priority Unassigned = 22 points\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Unassigned = 18 points\r\n\r\n\r\nSeepage Rank 2 x Rank 2 = 25 points\r\nSeepage Rank 2 x Rank 3 = 24 points\r\nSeepage Rank 2 x Priority Unassigned = 21 points\r\nSeepage Rank 2 x Unassigned = 17 points\r\n\r\n\r\nSeepage Rank 3 x Rank 3 = 23 points\r\nSeepage Rank 3 x Priority Unassigned = 20 points\r\nSeepage Rank 3 x Unassigned = 16 points\r\n\r\nPriority Unassigned x Priority Unassigned = 19 points\r\nPriority Unassigned x Unassigned = 15 points\r\n\r\nUnassigned x Unassigned = 14 points\r\n",

    {

        "baseLayer": "N",
        "serverUrl": "https://data.gns.cri.nz/webmaps/petroleum/wms",
        "visible": "Y",

        "toolTipField": "cluster",
        "showInLegend": "Y",
        "showLegendGraphic": "Y",
        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "N",
        "tooltip": "Cluster_Centres.shp (Cluster Centres) Object\r\n\r\nA computed centroid from all of the qualifying repeats. \r\n\r\nScore Percent (Scoreperce) is worked out by:\r\n\r\nSlick Ranking:\r\n\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Seepage Rank 1 = 28 points\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Seepage Rank 2 = 27 points\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Seepage Rank 3 = 26 points\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Priority Unassigned = 22 points\r\nSeepage Rank 1 x Unassigned = 18 points\r\n\r\n\r\nSeepage Rank 2 x Rank 2 = 25 points\r\nSeepage Rank 2 x Rank 3 = 24 points\r\nSeepage Rank 2 x Priority Unassigned = 21 points\r\nSeepage Rank 2 x Unassigned = 17 points\r\n\r\n\r\nSeepage Rank 3 x Rank 3 = 23 points\r\nSeepage Rank 3 x Priority Unassigned = 20 points\r\nSeepage Rank 3 x Unassigned = 16 points\r\n\r\nPriority Unassigned x Priority Unassigned = 19 points\r\nPriority Unassigned x Unassigned = 15 points\r\n\r\nUnassigned x Unassigned = 14 points\r\n\r\nScore is modified by distance using the following formula:\r\n\r\n(5000-DISTANCE) x SCORE\r\n\r\nIf multiple repeats then the score is averaged. \r\nThe score is then converted to a percentage from 50-100%. Below 50% is reserved for pollution repeats as all repeating slicks are deemed at least 50% significant. \r\n\r\nUse the information tool (\"i\" symbol) or database to find out the repeat information.\r\n",

        "tooltip": "Grid depicting the modelled depth, in metres, beneath sea level to the Basement horizon in the Northwest Province mapping area (Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins), for the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity. The grid was generated in Paradigm 2015 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of either the TWT or depth maps in this project. The depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 4.61), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. For more information about the depth conversion and gridding process used, please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23b. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire NWP area the "smoothness" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Taranaki Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas of the NWP such as the Deepwater Taranaki Basin to the west and Reinga Basin in the north, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 30 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. It is recognised that whilst the APP NWP seismic mapping was completed at an appropriate resolution for a frontier basin, GNS Science has over the past decade put significant effort into mapping, modelling, and depth conversion in the southern Taranaki Basin region (Bull et al., 2015).         "tooltip": "This grid depicts the interpreted vertical thickness (isochore) in metres between the P50 and N10 seismic horizons mapped within the Northwest Province of the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity (namely the Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). This isochore interval encompasses rocks of c. 35-21 Ma age (Oligocene-earliest Miocene). For more information about the seismic horizon naming scheme used in this project please refer to: Strogen, D.P.; King, P.R. 2014. A new Zealandia-wide seismic horizon naming scheme. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The TWT and depth grids, from which this grid was derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT or depth maps in this project. The TWT and depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 4.61), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire NWP area the "smoothness" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Taranaki Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas of the NWP such as the Deepwater Taranaki Basin to the west and Reinga Basin in the north, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 30 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. For further information on these data, please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23b.",

        "tooltip": "Grid depicting the modelled depth, in metres, beneath sea level to the K80 horizon in the Northwest Province mapping area (Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins), for the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity. The grid was generated in Paradigm 2015 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of either the TWT or depth maps in this project. The depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 4.61), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. For more information about the depth conversion and gridding process used, please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23b. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire NWP area the "smoothness" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Taranaki Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas of the NWP such as the Deepwater Taranaki Basin to the west and Reinga Basin in the north, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 30 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. It is recognised that whilst the APP NWP seismic mapping was completed at an appropriate resolution for a frontier basin, GNS Science has over the past decade put significant effort into mapping, modelling, and depth conversion in the southern Taranaki Basin region (Bull et al., 2015).         "showOpacitySlider": "Y",
        "tooltip": "Grid depicting the Transformation Ratio (gas generation) for marine source rocks of Paleocene age. The grid indicates predicted transformation of organic matter at the base of the unit regardless of source rock presence and richness. Multi-1D modelling was used to reconstruct the basin thermal history and to predict maturity at present day. Transformation ratio maps were produced using the BM1D basin modelling code developed by GNS Science which is based on the 1D finite-element conductive heat flow package Bassim. The Multi-1D basin simulation code is applied to 1 km x 1 km cells across the SEP basin grids. Stratigraphic thickness, age, temperature and paleobathymetric data are combined with mathematical relationships describing sediment properties during progressive compaction to derive burial and thermal maturity histories for each cell. Heat flow is applied at the base of the model, using an approach consistent with that described in Armstrong et al. (1996) to fit thermal calibration data. Stratigraphic thickness, lithological data and paleobathymetry data are based on seismic interpretation and paleogeographic maps developed under the APP program over the SEP. For further information on these data, please refer to: Sahoo, T.R. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2017. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Southeast Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23c.",

        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains contours that depict the interpreted depth below sea level in milliseconds two-way-time (TWT) to the P50 (c. 35 Ma; base-Oligocene; base of New Zealand Whaingaroan Stage) horizon in the Northwest Province of the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity (namely the Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). For more information about the seismic horizon naming scheme used in this project please refer to: Strogen, D.P.; King, P.R. 2014. A new Zealandia-wide seismic horizon naming scheme. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The TWT grids, from which these contours were derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT maps in this project. The TWT grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 4.61), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids, imported and contoured with Esri's ArcGIS software. Contour spacing is 250 ms. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire NWP area the \"smoothness\" of the TWT maps varies accordingly. In the central Taranaki Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas of the NWP such as the Deepwater Taranaki Basin to the west and Reinga Basin in the north, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 30 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. For further information on these data, please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science",

        "baseLayer": "N",
        "serverUrl": "https://data.gns.cri.nz/webmaps/petroleum/wms",

        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "Y",
        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains contours that depict the interpreted depth below sea level in milliseconds two-way-time (TWT) to the Seabed (0 Ma) horizon in the Northwest Province of the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity (namely the Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). For more information about the seismic horizon naming scheme used in this project please refer to: Strogen, D.P.; King, P.R. 2014. A new Zealandia-wide seismic horizon naming scheme. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The TWT grids, from which these contours were derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT maps in this project. The TWT grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 4.61), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids, imported and contoured with Esri's ArcGIS software. Contour spacing is 250 ms. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire NWP area the \"smoothness\" of the TWT maps varies accordingly. In the central Taranaki Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas of the NWP such as the Deepwater Taranaki Basin to the west and Reinga Basin in the north, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 30 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. For further information on these data, please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23b.",

        "tooltip": "This feature class contains polyline features for Pliocene volcanic centres at the seafloor and/or within the Pliocene sedimentary sequence as defined by 2D and 3D seismic reflection data. For larger volcanic centres both the volcanic apron and centre have been mapped. The volcanic apron is defined by a region surrounding the volcanic centre where seismic reflections from beneath the volcano are coherent and onlap of overlying reflectors onto the flanks of the volcano can be demonstrated.         "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "Y",
        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains polygon features that summarise the exploration potential of the Plio-Pleistocene succession within sedimentary basins in the Northwest Province (Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). Areas where all of the requirements for oil or gas accumulation are present are indicated as having high exploration potential. Areas where all the requirements are not optimum, but may be present are indicated as areas of moderate exploration potential. Areas of low exploration potential indicates that on the basis of currently available open-file information there is a high risk for one or more of the petroleum systems elements not being able to effectively contribute to the petroleum system in that area. It is important to note that a rating of low exploration potential does not conclusively rule it out; rather, there is a high degree of uncertainty associated with presence of one or more of the petroleum system elements. For any given prospective area, more detailed work and data acquisition would be required. For more information about these data please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016.         "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains polygon features that summarise the exploration potential of the Miocene succession within sedimentary basins in the Northwest Province (Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). Areas where all of the requirements for oil or gas accumulation are present are indicated as having high exploration potential. Areas where all the requirements are not optimum, but may be present are indicated as areas of moderate exploration potential. Areas of low exploration potential indicates that on the basis of currently available open-file information there is a high risk for one or more of the petroleum systems elements not being able to effectively contribute to the petroleum system in that area. It is important to note that a rating of low exploration potential does not conclusively rule it out; rather, there is a high degree of uncertainty associated with presence of one or more of the petroleum system elements. For any given prospective area, more detailed work and data acquisition would be required. For more information about these data please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23b.",

        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains polygon features that summarise the exploration potential of the Eocene succession within sedimentary basins in the Northwest Province (Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). Areas where all of the requirements for oil or gas accumulation are present are indicated as having high exploration potential. Areas where all the requirements are not optimum, but may be present are indicated as areas of moderate exploration potential. Areas of low exploration potential indicates that on the basis of currently available open-file information there is a high risk for one or more of the petroleum systems elements not being able to effectively contribute to the petroleum system in that area. It is important to note that a rating of low exploration potential does not conclusively rule it out; rather, there is a high degree of uncertainty associated with presence of one or more of the petroleum system elements. For any given prospective area, more detailed work and data acquisition would be required. For more information about these data please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016.         "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains polygon features that summarise the exploration potential of the Paleocene succession within sedimentary basins in the Northwest Province (Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). Areas where all of the requirements for oil or gas accumulation are present are indicated as having high exploration potential. Areas where all the requirements are not optimum, but may be present are indicated as areas of moderate exploration potential. Areas of low exploration potential indicates that on the basis of currently available open-file information there is a high risk for one or more of the petroleum systems elements not being able to effectively contribute to the petroleum system in that area. It is important to note that a rating of low exploration potential does not conclusively rule it out; rather, there is a high degree of uncertainty associated with presence of one or more of the petroleum system elements. For any given prospective area, more detailed work and data acquisition would be required. For more information about these data please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23b.",

        "opacity": 1.0,
        "showOpacitySlider": "N",
        "tooltip": "This data table is a compilation of all known onshore oil and gas seeps from published accounts spanning the late 1800s to 2014. Data is drawn from 312 references sourced from McLernon (1978) PR839 and 27 references that are derived from more recent publications. The data table includes 725 hydrocarbon based gas seeps and vents, 191 oil seeps, 40 oil and gas seeps, and 8 non-hydrocarbon gas seeps. The location, depositional basin, and other relevant geologic information, such as reservoir unit and lithology, are included as available from the original publication. Seeps are presented from all of New Zealands sedimentary basins as well as from localities outside of these basins (for example the Taupo Volcanogenic Zone, the axial mountain ranges and the Coromandel Peninsula). Geochemical data on the gas composition and carbon isotope compositions of methane and carbon dioxide and hydrogen isotope compositions of methane are provided for gas seeps as available from the published references. Additional information about the activity and history of each seep was extracted from the published references and included as series of comments in the table.",

        "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains Common Risk Segment (CRS) polygon features for denoting the risk of source rocks being absent within the Eocene succession in sedimentary basins in the Northwest Province (Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). Risk is depicted by a relatively simple \"traffic-light\" system: green colours denote low risk, orange denotes moderate risk, and red colours denote high risk. It is important to note that a rating of high risk (red) for this petroleum systems element does not conclusively rule it out; rather, it indicates that on the basis of currently available open-file information there is a high risk for that factor being able to effectively contribute to the petroleum system in that area. For any given prospective area, more detailed work and data acquisition would be required. For more information about these data please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016.         "tooltip": "This Feature Class contains contours that depict the interpreted depth below sea level (in metres) to the Basement seismic horizon, in 500 m intervals, as mapped within the Northwest Province of the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity (namely the Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). For more information about the seismic horizon naming scheme used in this project please refer to: Strogen, D.P.; King, P.R. 2014. A new Zealandia-wide seismic horizon naming scheme. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The depth grids, from which these contours were derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of either the TWT or depth maps in this project. The depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 4.61), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids, imported and contoured with Esri's ArcGIS software. Due to its large depth range the Basement horizon has been contoured at both 250 m and 500 m intervals. For more information about the depth conversion and gridding process used, please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23b. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire NWP area the \"smoothness\" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Taranaki Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well.         "tooltip": "This grid depicts the interpreted vertical thickness (isochore) in metres between the N10 and N60 seismic horizons mapped within the Northwest Province of the Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity (namely the Taranaki, Deepwater Taranaki, and Reinga-Northland basins). This isochore interval encompasses rocks of c. 21-04 Ma age (Early Miocene-Early Pliocene). For more information about the seismic horizon naming scheme used in this project please refer to: Strogen, D.P.; King, P.R. 2014. A new Zealandia-wide seismic horizon naming scheme. Lower Hutt, NZ: GNS Science. GNS Science report 2014/34. 20 p. The TWT and depth grids, from which this grid was derived, were generated in Paradigm 2015 SeisEarth software using an adaptive fitting algorithm and a grid resolution of 1 km x 1 km. Faults have not been incorporated into the regional-scale gridding of the TWT or depth maps in this project. The TWT and depth grids were then exported from SeisEarth (Zmap format), checked for internal consistency in Zetaware (Trinity 4.61), edited as needed to account for gridding errors and then exported as ArcView Ascii grids. Given the considerable variability in the spacing and density of 2D seismic data over the entire NWP area the "smoothness" of the depth maps varies accordingly. In the central Taranaki Basin, where seismic line spacing may be 5 km or less, the 1 km x 1 km grid resolution captures the geological complexity well. However, in areas of the NWP such as the Deepwater Taranaki Basin to the west and Reinga Basin in the north, seismic line spacing may be in the order of 15 to 30 km. In such areas the underlying geological complexity is only captured where seismic interpretation exists along the available 2D seismic lines. For further information on these data, please refer to: Arnot, M.J. and Bland, K.J. et al. (Compilers), 2016. Atlas of Petroleum Prospectivity, Northwest Province: ArcGIS geodatabase and technical report. GNS Science Data Series 23b.",

        "showOpacitySlider": "Y",
        "tooltip": "The Topo50 map series provides topographic mapping for the New Zealand mainland, the Chatham Islands, and offshore islands at 1:50,000 scale.\n\n\nAlong with the paper-based Topo50 map series, digital images of the maps are also publicly available.\n\nGeoreferenced raster digital images are provided at a resolution of 300 DPI. Georeferencing allows adjacent maps to be accurately and automatically aligned within GIS systems. \n\nFor more information, and a description of the georeferencing keys:\nhttp://www.linz.govt.nz/topography/topo-maps/topo50/digital-images\n\nPlease be aware of the following:\n\n- Representation of a road or track does not necessarily indicate public right of access.  For access rights, maps and other information, contact the New Zealand Walking Access Commission - www.walkingaccess.govt.nz \n\n- The Department of Conservation and other agencies should be contacted for the latest information on tracks and back country huts. Closed tracks are defined as being no longer maintained or passable and should not be used.  \n\n- Not all aerial wires, cableways and obstructions that could be hazardous to aircraft are held in the data. \n\n- Contours and spot elevations in forest and snow areas may be less accurate.\n\n- Not all pipelines including both underground and above ground are held in the data or shown on the printed maps.
